Introduction -:¶

Sentiment Analysis can be defined as the process of analyzing text data and categorizing them into Positive, Negative, or Neutral sentiments. Sentiment Analysis is used in many cases like Social Media Monitoring, Customer service, Brand Monitoring, political campaigns, etc.. Its Kaggle competition to find Tweet's Sentiment analysis .

Refrence:-https://www.kaggle.com/c/tweet-sentiment-extraction

Business problem: -¶

  1. Analyzing customer feedback such as social media conversations, product reviews, and survey responses allows companies to understand the customers emotions better which is becoming more essential to meet their needs.

  2. In this problem, we are given some text data along with their sentiment(positive/negative/neutral) and we need to find the phrases/words that best supports the sentiment.

  3. Using Deep Learning on training data (text and sentiment) have to predict selected_text(Phrase).

In [8]:
#https://studymachinelearning.com/jaccard-similarity-text-similarity-metric-in-nlp/
#https://towardsdatascience.com/overview-of-text-similarity-metrics-3397c4601f50
def Jaccard_Similarity(doc1, doc2): 
    
    # List the unique words in a document
    words_doc1 = set(doc1.lower().split()) 
    words_doc2 = set(doc2.lower().split())
    
    # Find the intersection of words list of doc1 & doc2
    intersection = words_doc1.intersection(words_doc2)

    # Find the union of words list of doc1 & doc2
    union = words_doc1.union(words_doc2)
        
    # Calculate Jaccard similarity score 
    # using length of intersection set divided by length of union set
    return float(len(intersection)) / len(union)

#https://www.kaggle.com/c/tweet-sentiment-extraction/discussion/138520
#Checking Jaccard_Similarity between text and selected text on nuteral sentiment
results_jaccard=[]

for ind,row in Neutral_df.iterrows():
    sentence1 = row.text
    sentence2 = row.selected_text

    jaccard_score = Jaccard_Similarity(sentence1,sentence2)
    results_jaccard.append([sentence1,sentence2,jaccard_score])

Text preprocessing¶

Text preprocessing is a method to clean the text data and make it ready to feed data to the model. Text data contains noise in various forms like emotions, punctuation, text in a different case

In [139]:
#we found some text are  like  "I don`t even remember what's on there!!!" 
# I`m like so upset with you.. haha.. you never told me the 411 
#have ` this special charector while converting Expand Contractions  its wont recognize the ` this char so inted of this would be 
#replace by ' so during converting Expand Contractions it will convert to Contractions like arn't to are not like this.
def removespecifchar(df):
  special_characters = "`"
  for k in range(len(df)):
    if(special_characters in df[k]):
      df[k]=df[k].replace("`","'")
In [140]:
#----------------------------Train data ----------------------------------------#

train_data['selected_text'] =removespecifchar(train_data['selected_text'])
#----------------------------Test data------------------------------------------#removespecifchar
test_data['text'] = removespecifchar(test_data['text'])

import re
def decontracted(text):
  for word in text.split():
    if word.lower() in CONTRACTION_MAP:
        text = text.replace(word, CONTRACTION_MAP[word.lower()])
    return text

Remove punctuation¶

In [126]:
def clean_text(text):
    '''Make text lowercase, remove text in square brackets,remove links,remove punctuation
    and remove words containing numbers.'''
    text = str(text).lower()
    text = re.sub('\[.*?\]', '', text)
    text = re.sub('https?://\S+|www\.\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub('<.*?>+', '', text)
    text = re.sub('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation), '', text)
    text = re.sub('\n', '', text)
    text = re.sub('\w*\d\w*', '', text)
    return text
In [127]:

#----------------------------Test data------------------------------------------#

In [128]:
STOPWORDS = set(nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english'))
def cleaning_stopwords(text):
    return " ".join([word for word in str(text).split() if word not in STOPWORDS])
In [129]:
